<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext:
```c
bool OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext(OS_object_iter_t *iter)
{
    OS_common_record_t *record;
    bool                got_next;

    got_next           = false;
    iter->token.obj_id = OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED;

    do
    {
        ++iter->token.obj_idx;
        if (iter->token.obj_idx >= iter->limit)
        {
            break;
        }

        record = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(iter->base, iter->token);
        if (iter->match == NULL || iter->match(iter->arg, &iter->token, record))
        {
            iter->token.obj_id = record->active_id;
            got_next           = true;
        }
    } while (!got_next);

    return got_next;
}
```
</target_code>
Please find suspicious code fragments in the code and report them. Other agents can not investigate other fragments that you do not report, so it is very important to find all suspicious fragments without missing any. Report the suspicious fragments AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.
explanation: No use of the C standard library string functions (including memcmp) is present in the provided code. The function only performs integer/pointer operations and checks: increments iter->token.obj_idx, numeric comparison (>= iter->limit), null-pointer check (iter->match == NULL), and assigns iter->token.obj_id from record->active_id. There are no char pointers, string literals, or calls to memcmp/strcmp/strncmp/strcasecmp/etc. The iter->match callback could potentially perform string comparisons, but its implementation is outside the provided code and therefore not part of this fragment. Consequently, there are no occurrences in this fragment that need investigation for Rule 21.14.
